WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.637 --> 00:00:03.470
MALE SPEAKER: We're in
for real treat today,

00:00:03.470 --> 00:00:07.960
we're here with Dr. Bernard
Roth who also goes by Bernie.

00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:10.300
So a little bit
about Dr. Roth, he's

00:00:10.300 --> 00:00:12.650
the Rodney H. Adams
professor of engineering,

00:00:12.650 --> 00:00:15.220
and the academic director
of the Hasso Plattner

00:00:15.220 --> 00:00:18.410
Institute of Design, also
known as the d.school

00:00:18.410 --> 00:00:20.290
at Stanford University.

00:00:20.290 --> 00:00:23.070
He graduated from the
City College of New York

00:00:23.070 --> 00:00:25.110
with a degree in
mechanical engineering.

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:29.040
He's a native New Yorker, and
he earned a master's degree

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:31.690
and a PhD In
mechanical engineering

00:00:31.690 --> 00:00:33.780
from Columbia University.

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:37.400
In 2012, the Columbia University
Engineering School Alumni

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:41.410
Association awarded him the
prestigious Egleston Medal

00:00:41.410 --> 00:00:43.600
for Distinguished
Engineering Achievement.

00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:45.690
And he lives in
Stanford, California.

00:00:45.690 --> 00:00:47.690
We have a pretty interactive
presentation today,

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:51.120
he's got a mic for Q&amp;A.
So it'll be good hour.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:53.102
Without further ado, Dr. Roth.

00:00:53.102 --> 00:00:55.512
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:58.767 --> 00:01:00.600
BERNARD ROTH: Thank you
for coming out here,

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:03.444
I have Google stock so
I won't waste your time.

00:01:03.444 --> 00:01:06.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:06.290 --> 00:01:10.710
This book that I wrote
is an expression of stuff

00:01:10.710 --> 00:01:13.390
that's been my life for
a very, very long time.

00:01:13.390 --> 00:01:17.210
When I first came out
to the valley in 1962,

00:01:17.210 --> 00:01:19.160
it was a very different place.

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:21.420
Not only was there no Google,
there were no start ups,

00:01:21.420 --> 00:01:23.030
essentially.

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:27.600
Hewlett Packard was
the big place in town.

00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:30.262
A lot of people would
always-- my students

00:01:30.262 --> 00:01:31.720
all would say that
some day they're

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:33.370
going to start a
company and all that,

00:01:33.370 --> 00:01:35.620
and there wasn't venture money.

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:37.540
Most of them never
did, and it reminded me

00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:40.230
of this story in
"The Iceman Cometh"

00:01:40.230 --> 00:01:42.420
where these guys are
sitting in the bar all day,

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:44.730
and they never leave
the bar, and they just

00:01:44.730 --> 00:01:46.940
talk about going out
and crossing the street.

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:49.780
So I felt, really, that
there was something

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:51.650
missing in people's education.

00:01:51.650 --> 00:01:53.850
So I started a class,
which eventually is called,

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:55.559
"The Designer in Society."

00:01:55.559 --> 00:01:56.850
The name doesn't mean anything.

00:01:56.850 --> 00:01:58.070
It's just a name.

00:01:58.070 --> 00:02:03.240
And the idea was, everyone got
to do a term project which they

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:07.130
chose, which was either get
rid of a problem in your life

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:09.740
or do something you've always
want to do and you've never

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:10.720
before.

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:12.540
And it could be things
like jumping out

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:13.630
of airplanes or whatever.

00:02:13.630 --> 00:02:16.820
It doesn't have to be anything
academic, or engineering,

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:18.060
or stuff like that.

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:21.990
And to fill the 10
weeks between that,

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:23.700
I had to do a lot of stuff.

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:26.070
So I developed a lot of
exercises and readings

00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:27.270
and things like that.

00:02:27.270 --> 00:02:33.210
And it's been going on since
1970, so that's a long time.

00:02:33.210 --> 00:02:37.000
Eventually, various
circumstances of my life

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.360
led to, "Well, I'm stuck
here on my sabbatical,

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:42.250
I might as well do
something useful."

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:44.120
So I decided I write a book.

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:45.759
Now the last time
I had that feeling

00:02:45.759 --> 00:02:47.425
was when I was young
assistant professor

00:02:47.425 --> 00:02:49.540
on my first
sabbatical in Holland,

00:02:49.540 --> 00:02:51.000
and I started to write a book.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.420
And it turned out to be
525 pages of all equations.

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:57.520
It took me nine years.

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:00.240
One reviewer said it was the
best book of the century.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:03.040
Another said it's the best
kinematics book ever written.

00:03:03.040 --> 00:03:04.680
And it sold 2,000 copies.

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:06.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:09.750
This book took less
than a year to write.

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:11.540
It's been in process
for three years.

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:13.650
It's been out two days.

00:03:13.650 --> 00:03:16.680
Amazon has run out of copies.

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:20.900
It went to the number one
list in business and advice

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:21.690
kind of things.

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:23.000
It's in the top hundred.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.590
The staff has chosen to read it.

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:26.050
So this is amazing.

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:26.685
No equations.

00:03:26.685 --> 00:03:28.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:33.780
So it's like bracketing my
life from serious scientist

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:35.900
to fuzzy guy.

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:40.030
But the fuzzy guy
stuff is useful.

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:42.240
It's amazing-- the
story-- they make me cry,

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:44.840
a lot of these stories
because it's changed

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:46.260
a lot of people's lives.

00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:48.080
And the funny thing
is, I thought it was me

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:51.490
and my magic in the classroom,
my insightfulness and all that.

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:53.290
But people have
been having galleys

00:03:53.290 --> 00:03:55.220
for a couple of
months around, and I

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:56.950
keep getting the same stories.

00:03:56.950 --> 00:03:59.680
"Bernie, I picked up
your book and I did this,

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:02.140
and I did that" and
all that, including

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:06.215
the woman who used to work
for the Washington Post,

00:04:06.215 --> 00:04:08.250
and now she works
at the d.school.

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:10.940
And she does our blog
page and all that stuff.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:13.690
And she was close to me from
the beginning with the book.

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:18.709
And when she got to read
the final copy, she said,

00:04:18.709 --> 00:04:21.417
"You know, I'm going to
stop trying to do something,

00:04:21.417 --> 00:04:22.750
I'm going to write my own book."

00:04:22.750 --> 00:04:24.630
And she's getting up
at 3:00 in the morning

00:04:24.630 --> 00:04:26.090
every morning writing a book.

00:04:26.090 --> 00:04:29.040
So I want warn you,
this can ruin your life.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:31.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:33.820
And the other insight
I had coming in here,

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:37.317
if these two guys called Larry
and Serge had taken my course,

00:04:37.317 --> 00:04:39.650
this company would be three
times bigger than it already

00:04:39.650 --> 00:04:41.015
is.

00:04:41.015 --> 00:04:44.800
But somehow they escaped
without seeing me there.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:47.710
Anyhow, I want to talk
to you, basically,

00:04:47.710 --> 00:04:51.390
about life, and problem
solving, and things like that.

00:04:51.390 --> 00:04:59.030
And if you read one of
the reviews on Amazon,

00:04:59.030 --> 00:05:00.200
you can read his reviews.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:03.590
My buddy, Bob Sutton, who wrote
a book, "Don't Hire Assholes,"

00:05:03.590 --> 00:05:06.350
or something like
that, he put up,

00:05:06.350 --> 00:05:09.600
"Well, Bernie thinks about the
world different than everyone

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:12.330
else, but it seems to
be very successful.

00:05:12.330 --> 00:05:14.670
So maybe you ought to
try some of his ideas."

00:05:14.670 --> 00:05:17.850
So I'm going to give you some
ideas, which up until Tuesday

00:05:17.850 --> 00:05:20.700
were just Bernie's bullshit,
but now it's written.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:22.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:22.910
So, this is real.

00:05:22.910 --> 00:05:24.470
This is real, folks.

00:05:24.470 --> 00:05:26.670
I've been getting away with
it for all these years,

00:05:26.670 --> 00:05:29.970
but now I can give you
book where it's real.

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:31.890
I started this stuff--
there's a company

00:05:31.890 --> 00:05:36.900
IDEO, you may or may not know
them, which are my students.

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:38.692
For years I would do
my stuff and people

00:05:38.692 --> 00:05:39.900
would say, "Well how's that?"

00:05:39.900 --> 00:05:41.900
I would say, "Well, that's
what they do at IDEO,

00:05:41.900 --> 00:05:43.040
so it's got to be OK."

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:44.270
So I had someone to point to.

00:05:44.270 --> 00:05:46.130
Now I don't need to
hide behind IDEO.

00:05:46.130 --> 00:05:47.960
I can just point to by book.

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:50.120
OK, so what do we
want to talk about?

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:53.100
Well, what I want to talk about
first is solving problems.

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:55.580
So the issue is,
you're all smart.

00:05:55.580 --> 00:05:58.620
Like Larry Page said, you all
deserve to be here, right?

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:01.730
So you got past that hurdle,
whoever reads that stuff.

00:06:01.730 --> 00:06:04.290
And I deal at Stanford
with a lot of smart people,

00:06:04.290 --> 00:06:08.070
and have a lot of smart friends,
and I'm pretty smart myself.

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:12.810
So how come we all mess up,
and we can't solve problems?

00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:14.380
In our lives we have problems.

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:15.770
In our work we have problems.

00:06:15.770 --> 00:06:21.270
How come we can't just do what
we want to do and it flows?

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:26.040
Well, you know, it's illogical.

00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:28.499
Even if we grasp for something
new, if you're really smart

00:06:28.499 --> 00:06:29.790
you should be able to solve it.

00:06:29.790 --> 00:06:31.660
So what is it that happens?

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:34.980
So I've noticed-- I have a life.

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:36.350
I've lived a long time.

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:37.950
And I've had a lot of problems.

00:06:37.950 --> 00:06:39.930
I notice my family
has a lot of problems.

00:06:39.930 --> 00:06:42.590
My friends have problems.

00:06:42.590 --> 00:06:44.640
We do a lot of work
at the d.school, a lot

00:06:44.640 --> 00:06:46.030
of problems around the world.

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:48.160
Before that, in the
design group in ME

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:50.520
we would do a lot of
projects for companies.

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:53.990
How come people get stuck?

00:06:53.990 --> 00:06:57.200
And I said, this is very
scientific, in my view

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:01.770
99.999% of the time,
it's because you're

00:07:01.770 --> 00:07:03.270
working on the wrong problem.

00:07:03.270 --> 00:07:04.590
It's as simple as that.

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:07.050
And what you've done is
you've taken an answer,

00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:09.160
and you assume
that's the question.

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:10.780
I'll explain that more later.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:13.890
And it's not a good answer
to what you want to work on.

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:17.070
So even if you solved it, it
really would kind of a crummy

00:07:17.070 --> 00:07:18.440
kludge.

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:21.220
But once you find the
right problem to work on,

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:25.190
it's generally easy
sailing and sometimes it's

00:07:25.190 --> 00:07:27.290
right in front of you.

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:30.550
So I'll give you a simple
example in my own life,

00:07:30.550 --> 00:07:32.740
and there's two points to this.

00:07:32.740 --> 00:07:36.070
The first point is, whatever
I tell you right now is not

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:38.430
like an inoculation for life.

00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:42.840
You have to keep looking at this
stuff, and it's a little hard.

00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:44.880
That's the tricky
part about it, just

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:46.660
knowing about it is not enough.

00:07:46.660 --> 00:07:49.300
You have to kind of check
yourself all the time.

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:54.665
So go back some years, and
I'm doing my guru number

00:07:54.665 --> 00:08:00.390
at KTH, which is the MIT
of Sweden in Stockholm.

00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:03.800
And things are going
great, but at night, I'm

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:06.320
losing sleep all
night long because I'm

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:07.960
near the retirement age.

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:10.560
In those days, there was a
thing called, "retirement age."

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:14.870
And I'm deciding, should I
retire or shouldn't I retire?

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:16.740
And I'm really losing
sleep over that.

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:18.870
In the middle of one
of my lectures I go,

00:08:18.870 --> 00:08:22.430
"hey, maybe I should apply
some of the stuff to myself."

00:08:22.430 --> 00:08:26.610
So that night I go home
and I say-- the trick is,

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:28.760
the starkness is to
ask yourself what

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:31.380
it would for you if
you solve your problem.

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:33.720
So I said to myself,
"Well, what's my problem?"

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:37.380
My problem is deciding whether
I should retire or not.

00:08:37.380 --> 00:08:41.000
And I said, "Well, what would do
for me if I solve the problem?"

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.039
I could stop worrying about
whether to retire or not.

00:08:44.039 --> 00:08:45.200
Simple as that.

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:48.280
So, the problem is
not the decision,

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:49.950
the problem is to stop worrying.

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:53.570
So how do you stop worrying
about whether to retire or not?

00:08:53.570 --> 00:08:54.617
It's a no brainer.

00:08:54.617 --> 00:08:55.950
You just stop worrying about it.

00:08:55.950 --> 00:08:57.000
So I stopped.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:58.940
And it's been many,
many years, and I never

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:00.410
worried about again.

00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:02.020
So it's a kind of
crummy example,

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:04.560
but that's the essence
of it, that you

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:05.980
have the wrong problem.

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:08.699
And often it's a little
subtle change in the thing,

00:09:08.699 --> 00:09:10.490
and you think you're
dealing with something

00:09:10.490 --> 00:09:13.910
which is life and death, and
it's not the right thing.

00:09:13.910 --> 00:09:15.290
So that's the model.

00:09:15.290 --> 00:09:19.406
So let's-- can we
write on this board?

00:09:19.406 --> 00:09:20.340
AUDIENCE: Yep.

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:21.600
BERNARD ROTH: Good.

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:24.950
Oh, and it has
markers, fantastic.

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:29.220
OK, so let's take an example so
this becomes really concrete.

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:31.680
And then we'll
apply to your life.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:37.530
So what I do with Stanford
students is this one.

00:09:37.530 --> 00:09:39.190
We'll do it with you guys too.

00:09:39.190 --> 00:09:42.100
So let's say, oh,
you're having trouble

00:09:42.100 --> 00:09:46.250
deciding getting married.

00:09:46.250 --> 00:09:49.840
So let's say your problem
is how to get married.

00:09:56.390 --> 00:09:59.280
And you've tried everything.

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:01.260
Most people it's not an issue.

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:03.070
They get married or
don't get married,

00:10:03.070 --> 00:10:04.390
but they don't worry about it.

00:10:04.390 --> 00:10:05.780
But let's say in
your case you're

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:07.392
really concerned about this.

00:10:07.392 --> 00:10:08.350
You've done everything.

00:10:08.350 --> 00:10:11.510
You've joined many
computer dating services.

00:10:11.510 --> 00:10:14.840
In the old days you would go
to every bar on the Camino, all

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:16.090
of that kind of stuff.

00:10:16.090 --> 00:10:19.030
And your friends are fixing
you up, and nothing works.

00:10:19.030 --> 00:10:20.520
Your parents are on your case.

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:22.600
And your older brother
is waiting for you

00:10:22.600 --> 00:10:24.550
to get out of the way
so he could get married

00:10:24.550 --> 00:10:26.300
to his true love, but
he can't get married

00:10:26.300 --> 00:10:27.470
because you haven't
gotten married, whatever

00:10:27.470 --> 00:10:29.060
it is, that whole drama.

00:10:29.060 --> 00:10:31.880
So let's say it just
doesn't work for you.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:36.080
So, you're stuck.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:38.810
And my method says,
probably you're

00:10:38.810 --> 00:10:40.950
stuck because this is
the wrong question.

00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:43.340
And the way you find what
the right question is,

00:10:43.340 --> 00:10:45.930
you say what would it do
for me if I solve this.

00:10:45.930 --> 00:10:49.030
What would it do for
me if I got married?

00:10:49.030 --> 00:10:51.810
So somebody give me an
answer, what would it

00:10:51.810 --> 00:10:53.190
do for you if you got married.

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:54.023
Someone.

00:10:54.023 --> 00:10:55.230
AUDIENCE: Your parents
will stop bugging you.

00:10:55.230 --> 00:10:55.820
BERNARD ROTH: Say it again.

00:10:55.820 --> 00:10:57.170
AUDIENCE: Your parents
will stop bugging you.

00:10:57.170 --> 00:10:58.128
BERNARD ROTH: OK great.

00:10:58.128 --> 00:11:00.510
All right, great.

00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:10.180
So how to get parents
to stop bugging you.

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:12.232
OK, so that's the problem.

00:11:12.232 --> 00:11:14.190
So the question is, how
do you get your parents

00:11:14.190 --> 00:11:15.320
to stop bugging you?

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:18.417
Well, even if you got
married they might not

00:11:18.417 --> 00:11:20.000
stop bugging you,
because then they're

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:21.900
going to want grandchildren,
blah, blah, blah.

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:23.040
So if they're going
to bug you, they're

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:24.123
going to keep bugging you.

00:11:24.123 --> 00:11:26.300
So it wouldn't even solve
that problem, often.

00:11:26.300 --> 00:11:28.680
And that's the problem
with this thing.

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:31.060
If it's hard, it's often
because it won't even

