selfish, but it's not selfish.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:06.550
And she could do
better for the people

00:22:06.550 --> 00:22:09.800
there if she were more
forthright with the thing.

00:22:09.800 --> 00:22:12.940
So that's one or hurdles
with solving problems,

00:22:12.940 --> 00:22:16.780
once you get the right problem
it works out fine, in general.

00:22:16.780 --> 00:22:19.450
Sometimes, you
sabotage yourself.

00:22:19.450 --> 00:22:22.650
And you sabotage
yourself with reasons.

00:22:22.650 --> 00:22:26.825
And the problem is you don't
say, "I have an excuse."

00:22:26.825 --> 00:22:28.850
You don't say, "I have
an excuse, Bernie."

00:22:28.850 --> 00:22:32.130
You say, "the reason is this--"
and the thing to understand

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:35.660
is, in terms of
personal behavior,

00:22:35.660 --> 00:22:37.420
all reasons are bullshit.

00:22:37.420 --> 00:22:39.990
You have no idea why
you're doing stuff,

00:22:39.990 --> 00:22:43.570
you just do it and you
make up a reason for it.

00:22:43.570 --> 00:22:45.671
And that's called being
a reasonable person.

00:22:45.671 --> 00:22:46.170
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:46.170 --> 00:22:49.070
If you don't have a reason,
you're not a reasonable person,

00:22:49.070 --> 00:22:50.110
right?

00:22:50.110 --> 00:22:52.970
If you say, "Why did you
come here to talk at Google?"

00:22:52.970 --> 00:22:56.360
If I say, "I don't
know," this guy's crazy.

00:22:56.360 --> 00:22:58.525
But if I say I came
because I was invited

00:22:58.525 --> 00:23:01.100
or I came because I want
to spread my wisdom,

00:23:01.100 --> 00:23:02.670
it's all reasonable, right?

00:23:02.670 --> 00:23:05.250
If I take this guy, he's
looking at his thing,

00:23:05.250 --> 00:23:08.169
I punch him in the nose, he
says, "Why did you do that?"

00:23:08.169 --> 00:23:09.210
If I say, "I don't know."

00:23:09.210 --> 00:23:10.279
I'm not reasonable.

00:23:10.279 --> 00:23:11.820
If you punch him in
the nose and say,

00:23:11.820 --> 00:23:14.430
"You look like the guy
who raped my neighbor."

00:23:14.430 --> 00:23:15.780
Then it's a good reason, right?

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:20.610
So, it's on that absurd
level that we do our reasons,

00:23:20.610 --> 00:23:22.200
and there have been
a lot of studies

00:23:22.200 --> 00:23:24.130
that show that
people's brains are

00:23:24.130 --> 00:23:27.300
such-- the part of the brain
that determines what you do

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:29.910
usually fires before the
part that figures out

00:23:29.910 --> 00:23:31.830
the reason for doing it.

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:34.360
So usually you do stuff
and then you say, why?

00:23:34.360 --> 00:23:36.600
And my favorite
example is, right now

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:38.880
my mouth is a little dry.

00:23:38.880 --> 00:23:41.190
Now if you say to me, "Why's
your mouth dry, Bernie?"

00:23:41.190 --> 00:23:42.780
I'd say, "well, I'm
speaking a lot."

00:23:42.780 --> 00:23:44.830
That's logical, right?

00:23:44.830 --> 00:23:48.540
But I don't tell you that I
was out last night drinking,

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:52.130
I don't tell you I'm
always dehydrated.

00:23:52.130 --> 00:23:54.240
I don't tell you a
lot of things which

00:23:54.240 --> 00:23:57.600
don't make me look as good
as, "I'm speaking now."

00:23:57.600 --> 00:24:00.750
So, in anything you do there's
a million reasons for it,

00:24:00.750 --> 00:24:03.110
and it's a matter of the
one that you pick out.

00:24:03.110 --> 00:24:07.330
To say something is a reason
for your behavior this a lie,

00:24:07.330 --> 00:24:09.230
and you need it
to be reasonable.

00:24:09.230 --> 00:24:11.230
So what I do is, if
you ask me reason,

00:24:11.230 --> 00:24:14.410
I'll tell you something, I'm
not going to be a jerk about it.

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:18.060
But if I know when I say it
that that reason is bullshit,

00:24:18.060 --> 00:24:20.490
then I'm going to say I'm
not going to do that again,

00:24:20.490 --> 00:24:24.470
and I'll do it again, but
eventually I'll stop doing it.

00:24:24.470 --> 00:24:31.200
So you have to realize that, in
fact, anything you call reason

00:24:31.200 --> 00:24:33.824
is not the reason for anything.

00:24:33.824 --> 00:24:35.615
So I don't want you to
take my word for it,

00:24:35.615 --> 00:24:37.280
I want you to do a
little experiment.

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:41.020
I want you to turn to
a person next to you

00:24:41.020 --> 00:24:45.380
and so I want you to do a little
exercise which goes like this.

00:24:45.380 --> 00:24:49.344
So you're going to work
with me, you're lucky.

00:24:49.344 --> 00:24:50.760
And the way it
goes is like this--

00:24:50.760 --> 00:24:52.850
I've done this workshop
a million times

00:24:52.850 --> 00:24:54.710
with the people I
work with at Stanford,

00:24:54.710 --> 00:24:58.360
my whole group in the design
group before the d.school.

00:24:58.360 --> 00:25:01.880
So, in our meeting
if some guy gets up--

00:25:01.880 --> 00:25:04.410
we have one professor who's
always crabbing about stuff.

00:25:04.410 --> 00:25:06.430
So he gets up and he
says, "Well the reason

00:25:06.430 --> 00:25:08.350
I can't do this is
the Dean said--"

00:25:08.350 --> 00:25:11.740
Everyone goes "That's
a good reason."

00:25:11.740 --> 00:25:16.050
With the emphasis on the O's,
which means it's bullshit.

00:25:16.050 --> 00:25:18.075
So in my parlance,
"It's a good reason"

00:25:18.075 --> 00:25:19.670
means it's not a reason at all.

00:25:19.670 --> 00:25:22.490
So if she's my
partner here, I say,

00:25:22.490 --> 00:25:24.000
"the reason why
my mouth is dry is

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:25.250
because I'm talking too much."

00:25:25.250 --> 00:25:27.456
She says, "That's
a good reason."

00:25:27.456 --> 00:25:27.956
Go ahead.

00:25:27.956 --> 00:25:29.255
AUDIENCE: That's a good reason.

00:25:29.255 --> 00:25:31.380
BERNARD ROTH: OK, now I
say, the reason I came here

00:25:31.380 --> 00:25:33.120
is because I was invited.

00:25:33.120 --> 00:25:34.710
AUDIENCE: That's a good reason.

00:25:34.710 --> 00:25:38.270
BERNARD ROTH: OK, so everything
I said is true, OK, it's true,

00:25:38.270 --> 00:25:41.780
but it's not the reason.

00:25:41.780 --> 00:25:43.900
Because I could have been
invited and not come,

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:45.552
I could have come
uninvited also.

00:25:45.552 --> 00:25:47.010
There's a lot of
different things--

00:25:47.010 --> 00:25:47.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:47.510 --> 00:25:49.426
--so it's kind of funny,
you know what I mean?

00:25:49.426 --> 00:25:50.279
And why did I come?

00:25:50.279 --> 00:25:52.570
Did I come because I want
you to think I'm a great man?

00:25:52.570 --> 00:25:54.740
Did I come because I
want to sell books?

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:56.871
There's a million
reasons in there,

00:25:56.871 --> 00:25:58.370
and I'm going to
pick the one that's

00:25:58.370 --> 00:26:02.140
going to make me look the
coolest, that's my self image.

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:04.510
I want you to experience
that for yourself.

00:26:04.510 --> 00:26:06.980
So what I'm going to ask you
to do is turn to your partner

00:26:06.980 --> 00:26:09.640
and I'm going to first tell
her a whole bunch of reasons,

00:26:09.640 --> 00:26:11.810
she's going to tell me
each one is a good reason,

00:26:11.810 --> 00:26:14.120
and then at some point
I'll say switch roles.

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:15.800
And then she'll
tell me her reasons,

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:18.870
and I'll say "That's a good
reason." for each of them.

00:26:18.870 --> 00:26:20.960
OK, you get the idea?

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:24.100
And if you do that, you're
gonna get a reward from me.

00:26:24.100 --> 00:26:28.317
All right, so please
turn to a partner.

00:26:28.317 --> 00:26:29.150
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:26:32.510 --> 00:26:35.030
And if you don't have a
partner, raise your hand.

00:26:36.594 --> 00:26:37.760
AUDIENCE: A reason for what?

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:38.190
BERNARD ROTH: What's that?

00:26:38.190 --> 00:26:39.295
AUDIENCE: A reason for what?

00:26:39.295 --> 00:26:40.130
For why we're here?

00:26:40.130 --> 00:26:42.171
BERNARD ROTH: For anything--
(YELLING OVER CROWD)

00:26:42.171 --> 00:26:45.270
one minute, one minute, one
minute, one minute, one minute,

00:26:45.270 --> 00:26:46.250
one minute.

00:26:46.250 --> 00:26:49.810
He asked me a very [INAUDIBLE]
question, a reason for what?

00:26:49.810 --> 00:26:54.090
Reasons for anything, but take
real things in your life, OK.

00:26:54.090 --> 00:26:57.660
Like whatever happens in your
life, the reason I'm here,

00:26:57.660 --> 00:26:59.820
or the reason I'm going
home tonight, or the reason

00:26:59.820 --> 00:27:01.700
I went to the movies yesterday.

00:27:01.700 --> 00:27:04.120
Just real stuff in
your life and just

00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:06.340
put a reason for your behavior.

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:09.460
So the reason is for your
behavior, real things

00:27:09.460 --> 00:27:11.474
in your life, the behavior, OK?

00:27:11.474 --> 00:27:13.307
AUDIENCE: And can you
say it's a good reason

00:27:13.307 --> 00:27:14.420
or it's a bad reason?

00:27:14.420 --> 00:27:17.020
BERNARD ROTH: No, always,
"It's a good reason."

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:17.960
They're all bad.

00:27:17.960 --> 00:27:20.370
What you don't understand,
she asked, can you

00:27:20.370 --> 00:27:24.110
say any reason-- there is no
good reason, this is a joke,

00:27:24.110 --> 00:27:25.450
always it's a bad reason.

00:27:25.450 --> 00:27:28.160
They're bad in the sense
that they're not uniquely

00:27:28.160 --> 00:27:30.030
the reason for anything.

00:27:30.030 --> 00:27:32.730
They're a reason and the
fact that you're singling

00:27:32.730 --> 00:27:35.849
that out is the problem, OK.

00:27:35.849 --> 00:27:36.682
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:27:42.590 --> 00:27:47.340
OK, thank you, thank
you, thank you.

00:27:47.340 --> 00:27:48.620
You get the idea.

00:27:48.620 --> 00:27:50.870
So one of the ones she does
did triggered something

00:27:50.870 --> 00:27:52.230
in me which I love very much.

00:27:52.230 --> 00:27:55.790
I was at a PhD exam up at
Stanford in the ed school

00:27:55.790 --> 00:27:59.020
and we're about to start but
there was a professor who

00:27:59.020 --> 00:28:02.450
was coming late, she happened
to be a person from Berkeley.

00:28:02.450 --> 00:28:06.080
And they said, "Oh she's
coming from Berkeley."

00:28:06.080 --> 00:28:07.850
Like that's OK to be late.

00:28:07.850 --> 00:28:10.680
And she just triggered that,
she said, "The reason I was late

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:12.510
is I came from the
other building."

00:28:12.510 --> 00:28:15.584
That's the bullshit I'm trying
to get you to understand.

00:28:15.584 --> 00:28:17.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:17.280 --> 00:28:22.130
We do that to ourselves all
the time, it's just an excuse,

00:28:22.130 --> 00:28:25.530
she didn't leave in time,
she didn't leave in time,

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:27.210
among other reasons.

00:28:27.210 --> 00:28:31.470
And that's what we do, so it's
so obvious when you see it.

00:28:31.470 --> 00:28:33.430
And the problem
is that I've just

00:28:33.430 --> 00:28:37.960
ruined your life because you're
always using bullshit reasons

00:28:37.960 --> 00:28:41.150
and all the people in your life
are using bullshit reasons.

00:28:41.150 --> 00:28:43.020
So the first thing
I've got to do in order

00:28:43.020 --> 00:28:45.220
to make, at least, that
you won't get killed

00:28:45.220 --> 00:28:49.730
and lose your relationship, do
not try this at home, please

00:28:49.730 --> 00:28:50.750
do not try this.

00:28:50.750 --> 00:28:54.420
It's OK to say, "hey we had this
crazy professor today at work,

00:28:54.420 --> 00:28:55.870
and he said reasons
are bullshit."

00:28:55.870 --> 00:28:57.750
That's OK, but
what you can't say

00:28:57.750 --> 00:28:59.110
is your reasons are bullshit.

00:28:59.110 --> 00:29:01.020
I have never said
that to my wife,

00:29:01.020 --> 00:29:02.910
I have never said
that to my friends,

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:04.930
I've never said it
to my family, I never

00:29:04.930 --> 00:29:06.385
say it to the guys
I bike with who

00:29:06.385 --> 00:29:09.850
are full of bullshit
reasons for everything.

00:29:09.850 --> 00:29:13.010
Do not do that, give
them a copy of my book,

00:29:13.010 --> 00:29:14.350
that's the way out of that.

00:29:14.350 --> 00:29:15.600
That will do it, really.

00:29:15.600 --> 00:29:17.740
Do not-- just fix yourself.

00:29:17.740 --> 00:29:20.090
But it's so simple
when you see that, when

00:29:20.090 --> 00:29:22.680
you see how we use
reasons all the time,

00:29:22.680 --> 00:29:26.360
they're just excuses, and once
you get past that you'll change

00:29:26.360 --> 00:29:27.910
your behavior if you want to.

00:29:27.910 --> 00:29:30.210
Now it doesn't happen,
necessarily, the next time,

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:31.460
but it will change.

00:29:31.460 --> 00:29:33.480
And I've lived through
that many times.

00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:35.780
So the idea is, it's a
really good framework

00:29:35.780 --> 00:29:38.990
to have in the back of your mind
that all reasons are bullshit.

00:29:38.990 --> 00:29:41.967
And we need them socially,
we have to be reasonable.

00:29:41.967 --> 00:29:44.050
But we don't need to keep
repeating the same thing

00:29:44.050 --> 00:29:46.520
if we realize what
I just is bullshit

00:29:46.520 --> 00:29:48.230
and I don't want
to do it again, I

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:49.920
don't want to come late again.

00:29:49.920 --> 00:29:51.740
And then you will
come late again,

00:29:51.740 --> 00:29:54.330
but eventually you'll learn
to leave 10 minutes earlier,

00:29:54.330 --> 00:29:55.250
If you want to.

00:29:55.250 --> 00:29:57.690
And if you don't you'll
have a good life without it,

00:29:57.690 --> 00:29:58.660
but that's the point.

00:29:58.660 --> 00:30:03.430
Yes, Let me get-- I've been
remiss in giving people

00:30:03.430 --> 00:30:03.930
the mic.

00:30:03.930 --> 00:30:04.992
I'm sorry.

00:30:04.992 --> 00:30:06.800
AUDIENCE: That's OK.

00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:08.620
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:30:08.620 --> 00:30:09.460
So I totally agree--

00:30:09.460 --> 00:30:10.350
BERNARD ROTH: OK.

00:30:10.350 --> 00:30:11.850
AUDIENCE: --but I
wonder whether you

00:30:11.850 --> 00:30:15.550
think that for everything we
do there's a lot of reasons

00:30:15.550 --> 00:30:17.550
and there isn't one
predominant one,

00:30:17.550 --> 00:30:19.330
and just arbitrarily
do something.

00:30:19.330 --> 00:30:20.990
Or there's some deep
reason that we're

00:30:20.990 --> 00:30:23.520
not aware of that's
somehow subconscious

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:25.260
and is driving our behavior.

00:30:25.260 --> 00:30:28.810
BERNARD ROTH: Well, my belief
is that there are many reasons

00:30:28.810 --> 00:30:30.810
and there's a veil--
so the ultimate reason

00:30:30.810 --> 00:30:34.020
is some great ancestor had
sex, if they didn't, you

00:30:34.020 --> 00:30:34.801
wouldn't be here.

00:30:34.801 --> 00:30:36.300
So that's the reason
for everything,

00:30:36.300 --> 00:30:37.750
but that seems absurd.

00:30:37.750 --> 00:30:39.910
But it goes that way,
you know, there's

00:30:39.910 --> 00:30:41.210
a whole hierarchy of reasons.

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:43.050
Some seem more
relevant because they

00:30:43.050 --> 00:30:45.560
are more recent and all that.

00:30:45.560 --> 00:30:49.380
However, what you
choose to do is not

00:30:49.380 --> 00:30:52.490
necessarily related to what
seems like the obvious reason

00:30:52.490 --> 00:30:53.110
right now.

00:30:53.110 --> 00:30:57.169
So, our friend from Greece
left, but there may be deep--

00:30:57.169 --> 00:30:58.710
I don't know her
well and stuff like,

00:30:58.710 --> 00:31:00.510
and I understand what
she's talking about,

00:31:00.510 --> 00:31:01.980
of course, it's
not unreasonable,

00:31:01.980 --> 00:31:03.890
but that reason
for that behavior

00:31:03.890 --> 00:31:05.120
may go back to her childhood.

00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:06.930
It may go back to
what her mother did,

00:31:06.930 --> 00:31:08.750
or how her parents rated her.

00:31:08.750 --> 00:31:11.250
It's not as simple
as you think is,

00:31:11.250 --> 00:31:13.240
we're all very
complex beings, we're

00:31:13.240 --> 00:31:16.150
formed by heredity
and environment,

00:31:16.150 --> 00:31:19.260
and the things we do,
we just do and then

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:23.160
we make things that make
our self image seem OK.

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:28.710
But if we remove the things, you
still have that behavior often,

00:31:28.710 --> 00:31:31.910
or not, I don't know.

00:31:31.910 --> 00:31:32.800
And who cares?

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:33.700
I mean I don't care.

00:31:33.700 --> 00:31:35.620
It's not my research, I
don't care about that.

00:31:35.620 --> 00:31:38.490
What I care about is functioning
and making myself a better

00:31:38.490 --> 00:31:41.310
functioning person and having
a better life for myself

00:31:41.310 --> 00:31:42.580
and the people around you.

00:31:42.580 --> 00:31:45.060
And I'm telling you if
you get rid of reasons

00:31:45.060 --> 00:31:46.360
it will work much better.

00:31:46.360 --> 00:31:49.870
A simple example in my life,
I get from China, and India,

00:31:49.870 --> 00:31:53.380
and all over the world maybe
three or four emails a week,

00:31:53.380 --> 00:31:57.010
"Professor, I'd like to
come and do a PhD with you."

00:31:57.010 --> 00:31:59.320
And I used to give
all-- I'm sorry,

00:31:59.320 --> 00:32:02.610
I don't have enough money in my
group, I'm going on sabbatical,

00:32:02.610 --> 00:32:05.629
and it's all bullshit because
if I want to take anybody

00:32:05.629 --> 00:32:07.920
there's nothing that would
stop me from taking someone.

00:32:07.920 --> 00:32:11.260
So the bottom line is, I just
don't want to take that person,

00:32:11.260 --> 00:32:14.020
and I just say, "I'm
sorry I can't help you."

00:32:14.020 --> 00:32:17.850
I get most back a, "thank
you for answering my email,

00:32:17.850 --> 00:32:18.654
professor."

00:32:18.654 --> 00:32:20.070
When I used to
give reasons they'd

00:32:20.070 --> 00:32:24.050
go-- if I say I don't have
enough money in my research

00:32:24.050 --> 00:32:26.280
group, "I have a rich
uncle, he'll do this--"

00:32:26.280 --> 00:32:29.120
and it goes on, and on, and on,
and it's totally dysfunctional.

00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:30.900
I'm not going to take
the person anyway.

00:32:30.900 --> 00:32:33.560
So just trying to make them
feel nice with the reasons

00:32:33.560 --> 00:32:35.440
actually makes it worse.

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:39.410
Often we give reasons to make
it feel nicer for someone else,

00:32:39.410 --> 00:32:41.660
we're really trying to make
it easier for ourselves.

00:32:41.660 --> 00:32:44.370
If you just say what you
do without the excuses

00:32:44.370 --> 00:32:46.270
and the reasons, is fine.

