00:43:53.210 --> 00:43:55.280
that came out of
the Big Bang, who

00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:56.770
knows why, I don't know why.

00:43:56.770 --> 00:43:59.610
But it's so complicated
for your behavior,

00:43:59.610 --> 00:44:02.580
it's not a simple thing
of cause and effect.

00:44:02.580 --> 00:44:05.795
And when you make the simple
cause effect model, it's great,

00:44:05.795 --> 00:44:08.960
it's functional, it makes
you a reasonable person,

00:44:08.960 --> 00:44:11.820
and it's fine, keep it all
the time, don't mess with it.

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:14.730
However, there are times
when it gets in your way,

00:44:14.730 --> 00:44:17.810
and you're letting
yourself off the hook.

00:44:17.810 --> 00:44:20.840
You know, like she
got here because she's

00:44:20.840 --> 00:44:23.130
in a distant building.

00:44:23.130 --> 00:44:25.000
I don't care, it's not
that life and death,

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.470
but it's a good
example of this thing.

00:44:27.470 --> 00:44:30.080
She got here because
she came late,

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:31.870
and she's late, that's all.

00:44:31.870 --> 00:44:34.690
She doesn't know why she's late.

00:44:34.690 --> 00:44:37.910
It could be, whatever
it is, I don't know.

00:44:37.910 --> 00:44:40.170
It could be her parents
were always late,

00:44:40.170 --> 00:44:42.010
it could be she
grew up in a culture

00:44:42.010 --> 00:44:43.620
where the lateness didn't count.

00:44:43.620 --> 00:44:47.184
I don't know, I don't know what
it is, and it doesn't matter.

00:44:47.184 --> 00:44:48.725
All I'm saying is
take responsibility

00:44:48.725 --> 00:44:51.090
for your behavior,
and don't let yourself

00:44:51.090 --> 00:44:54.760
off the hook with reasons
because they're just excuses.

00:44:54.760 --> 00:44:57.420
And if you label them as
excuses, you wouldn't do it.

00:44:57.420 --> 00:45:04.630
And you're sugar coating it by
saying it's a reason, it's not,

00:45:04.630 --> 00:45:07.540
and you don't know the reason,
that's what I'm saying.

00:45:07.540 --> 00:45:11.230
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering
if you'd thought, maybe,

00:45:11.230 --> 00:45:16.500
about the role of the poor and
thinking trying versus doing?

00:45:16.500 --> 00:45:20.030
Is there any kind of
differences in say, maybe

00:45:20.030 --> 00:45:22.240
a socioeconomically
disadvantaged person

00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:26.950
couldn't buy movie tickets
to a sold out show?

00:45:26.950 --> 00:45:29.390
Is it just limited
doing opportunities,

00:45:29.390 --> 00:45:31.420
or how do you do that?

00:45:31.420 --> 00:45:33.670
BERNARD ROTH: Well, everyone
has different strategies.

00:45:33.670 --> 00:45:35.140
So if I'm a rich
guy I could buy,

00:45:35.140 --> 00:45:37.340
if I'm a poor guy i could
steal, I don't know,

00:45:37.340 --> 00:45:40.300
it's whatever-- I could
beg or I could to give you

00:45:40.300 --> 00:45:41.560
a heart rendering story.

00:45:41.560 --> 00:45:44.620
You know, "My brother's in
the theater and he's sick

00:45:44.620 --> 00:45:46.620
and I have to, could I
please have your ticket?"

00:45:46.620 --> 00:45:49.690
I don't know, whatever it
takes, that's the whole point.

00:45:49.690 --> 00:45:52.219
There's no right answer
to it, it's just,

00:45:52.219 --> 00:45:53.760
whatever it takes
I'm going to do it,

00:45:53.760 --> 00:45:54.850
I'm going to get it done.

00:45:54.850 --> 00:45:56.800
And often you feel
really proud of yourself,

00:45:56.800 --> 00:45:59.140
I feel really proud that
I got those two tickets

00:45:59.140 --> 00:46:01.100
and I'm telling the
whole world about it.

00:46:01.100 --> 00:46:03.400
My wife hates when
I tell the story,

00:46:03.400 --> 00:46:06.280
but it's so clearly that thing.

00:46:06.280 --> 00:46:08.490
And there's no one
answer, and money may not

00:46:08.490 --> 00:46:11.850
work in some cases, although
it often does work pretty well.

00:46:11.850 --> 00:46:13.560
But it doesn't matter
what the answer

00:46:13.560 --> 00:46:16.120
is, if you have a
technical problem to solve,

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:18.430
ammonium may not
work with that thing.

00:46:18.430 --> 00:46:20.890
But some different way
of approaching it will,

00:46:20.890 --> 00:46:24.020
and whatever it is.

00:46:24.020 --> 00:46:27.660
I once had this experience, I
couldn't solve a math problem,

00:46:27.660 --> 00:46:31.650
a very tough problem, and I
was going to give a talk on it

00:46:31.650 --> 00:46:33.910
and I had given the
inflated title where

00:46:33.910 --> 00:46:37.130
I could solve the general case.

00:46:37.130 --> 00:46:39.860
I was, in my mind, getting
ready for the talk the next day

00:46:39.860 --> 00:46:43.290
and I said, "the reason I can't
solve the general case is--"

00:46:43.290 --> 00:46:44.790
And as I started
to give the reason,

00:46:44.790 --> 00:46:47.550
it was clear I could
solve the general case.

00:46:47.550 --> 00:46:50.430
But I had never let
go of the reason,

00:46:50.430 --> 00:46:52.550
I realized it was
a bullshit reason,

00:46:52.550 --> 00:46:55.330
so it even works
and technical stuff.

00:46:55.330 --> 00:46:57.210
You don't know the
reasons for stuff,

00:46:57.210 --> 00:46:59.726
you know what happens,
that's all you know.

00:46:59.726 --> 00:47:01.710
And you don't need
to know the reasons,

00:47:01.710 --> 00:47:04.370
the reasons are
nonsense, they're not

00:47:04.370 --> 00:47:08.730
taking responsibility for
what the situation is.

00:47:08.730 --> 00:47:10.320
Just use it a little
bit, you'll see,

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:12.760
it doesn't matter if you
believe me and it makes sense

00:47:12.760 --> 00:47:14.590
or doesn't, just test it out.

00:47:14.590 --> 00:47:16.840
The next time you're
about to give a reason,

00:47:16.840 --> 00:47:18.400
if you don't have to, just stop.

00:47:18.400 --> 00:47:22.780
Just say what's going on
and what you're going to do.

00:47:22.780 --> 00:47:23.660
Anyone else?

00:47:23.660 --> 00:47:26.120
Yes, how are you, the
stickers are going.

00:47:26.120 --> 00:47:29.590
So here's this and here's this.

00:47:29.590 --> 00:47:31.980
AUDIENCE: I was just thinking
that, potentially, reasons

00:47:31.980 --> 00:47:34.190
also show for great companies.

00:47:34.190 --> 00:47:37.520
Like companies without bullshit
reasons get things done,

00:47:37.520 --> 00:47:40.950
and do you think that's
true, or have you

00:47:40.950 --> 00:47:42.946
seen any examples of that?

00:47:42.946 --> 00:47:44.440
BERNARD ROTH: Of what?

00:47:44.440 --> 00:47:46.890
AUDIENCE: Good companies that
don't-- that have given up

00:47:46.890 --> 00:47:47.390
reasons--

00:47:47.390 --> 00:47:48.723
BERNARD ROTH: The whole company?

00:47:48.723 --> 00:47:50.370
AUDIENCE: I don't know.

00:47:50.370 --> 00:47:55.580
BERNARD ROTH: It's too general
a question for me, I don't know.

00:47:55.580 --> 00:47:57.930
You know, you get
it, actually, when

00:47:57.930 --> 00:48:00.330
people get caught with their
fingers in the cookie jars.

00:48:00.330 --> 00:48:04.220
Like, so when good
companies do something bad,

00:48:04.220 --> 00:48:06.772
they'll generally admit
it and when bad companies

00:48:06.772 --> 00:48:08.480
do something bad, they
generally give you

00:48:08.480 --> 00:48:10.690
all sorts of reasons for it.

00:48:10.690 --> 00:48:15.250
I don't know if that's true,
but that's sort of my idea.

00:48:15.250 --> 00:48:18.050
In fact, you get that all
the time, even in politics.

00:48:18.050 --> 00:48:24.070
Like Clinton and Nixon got into
more trouble by saying they

00:48:24.070 --> 00:48:26.540
didn't do it than if
they said they did it.

00:48:26.540 --> 00:48:28.950
You know, "I did it.

00:48:28.950 --> 00:48:32.450
Something happened in the
Oval Office, I did it."

00:48:32.450 --> 00:48:38.000
Or, Nixon, "Yes, we
had the burglars."

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:39.870
Just by not doing
it and they give you

00:48:39.870 --> 00:48:44.630
all these reasons and stuff like
that, it just becomes messy.

00:48:44.630 --> 00:48:46.880
But maybe people are getting
away with it all the time

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:48.880
and we just don't know about it.

00:48:48.880 --> 00:48:51.074
OK, other questions?

00:48:51.074 --> 00:48:52.740
AUDIENCE: It seems
like you could end up

00:48:52.740 --> 00:48:55.840
being in a doing state, but
end up working on something

00:48:55.840 --> 00:48:58.420
that is genuinely impossible.

00:48:58.420 --> 00:48:59.550
You've never run into that?

00:48:59.550 --> 00:49:02.104
BERNARD ROTH: You mean
something impossible?

00:49:02.104 --> 00:49:02.770
AUDIENCE: Yeah--

00:49:02.770 --> 00:49:03.620
BERNARD ROTH: Yeah, sure, sure.

00:49:03.620 --> 00:49:04.860
AUDIENCE: Like I'm gonna
go to the sun [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:04.860 --> 00:49:06.401
BERNARD ROTH: Well,
if you're working

00:49:06.401 --> 00:49:10.150
on something that's
impossible, then you're never

00:49:10.150 --> 00:49:12.220
going to solve it, right?

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:14.650
Is that your definition
of impossible?

00:49:14.650 --> 00:49:15.650
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I guess.

00:49:15.650 --> 00:49:17.650
BERNARD ROTH: So the
question is, "What would it

00:49:17.650 --> 00:49:19.249
do for you if you solved it?"

00:49:19.249 --> 00:49:21.040
AUDIENCE: Oh, so you're
back to the first--

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:21.970
BERNARD ROTH: Well,
the idea is, let's

00:49:21.970 --> 00:49:24.511
say you're working on something
you don't know is impossible.

00:49:24.511 --> 00:49:25.632
Let's say a simple case.

00:49:25.632 --> 00:49:27.840
Let's say it's impossible
for you to ever get married

00:49:27.840 --> 00:49:30.890
because you have bad breath,
no one ever wants to marry you.

00:49:30.890 --> 00:49:33.450
So no matter what you do, you're
never going to get married.

00:49:33.450 --> 00:49:35.860
So the question is,
"What's it going

00:49:35.860 --> 00:49:37.810
to do for you if
you go married?"

00:49:37.810 --> 00:49:40.442
So if it's, "I'm going
to get companionship,"

00:49:40.442 --> 00:49:42.150
well you can get a
dog, the dog might not

00:49:42.150 --> 00:49:44.000
care about the bad breath.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.450
Or if you hire
someone, enough money,

00:49:46.450 --> 00:49:48.080
they don't care about
it, we know that.

00:49:48.080 --> 00:49:51.290
So you're working
your way around it,

00:49:51.290 --> 00:49:56.300
that constraint is gone
because somehow you

00:49:56.300 --> 00:49:58.650
thought you were going to get
it out of getting married,

00:49:58.650 --> 00:50:01.380
but you can get companionship
a lot of other ways.

00:50:01.380 --> 00:50:03.340
So that's the idea.

00:50:03.340 --> 00:50:06.470
AUDIENCE: I love that you
talked about the delineation,

00:50:06.470 --> 00:50:09.830
the difference between
trying and doing,

00:50:09.830 --> 00:50:12.252
and there are two real
stages that exist.

00:50:12.252 --> 00:50:14.210
And you also mentioned
that most of the time we

00:50:14.210 --> 00:50:16.460
don't know the reasons behind
why we're doing things.

00:50:16.460 --> 00:50:18.010
So let's say you've been
on the journey for a while,

00:50:18.010 --> 00:50:19.430
you've been trying,
and you've started

00:50:19.430 --> 00:50:21.679
to identify some of those
reasons that are keeping you

00:50:21.679 --> 00:50:24.670
from your-- like the four
things we worry about doing.

00:50:24.670 --> 00:50:26.305
And you're starting
to feel kind of bad

00:50:26.305 --> 00:50:28.180
about yourself, because
you know the reasons,

00:50:28.180 --> 00:50:29.804
but you're not
making the changes

00:50:29.804 --> 00:50:31.220
to get where you
want to go and be

00:50:31.220 --> 00:50:34.060
an achiever or a
doer in these areas.

00:50:34.060 --> 00:50:35.875
Can you comment
at all on-- what's

00:50:35.875 --> 00:50:37.750
the breaking point,
what's the turning point,

00:50:37.750 --> 00:50:39.320
is it different for everybody?

00:50:39.320 --> 00:50:41.452
What's the transition
from trying to doing?

00:50:41.452 --> 00:50:42.410
What does it look like?

00:50:42.410 --> 00:50:43.760
BERNARD ROTH: So if
you're doing, no matter

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:45.880
what comes at you, you're
going to handle it.

00:50:52.070 --> 00:50:55.160
If you're trying it may
work, but if something comes

00:50:55.160 --> 00:50:57.230
at you to block you, you're
going to be deterred,

00:50:57.230 --> 00:50:58.313
you're not going to do it.

00:50:58.313 --> 00:51:00.150
So that's the difference
in the two states.

00:51:00.150 --> 00:51:01.540
And you can see
what's happening,

00:51:01.540 --> 00:51:03.980
and it's clearly you're
getting the result

00:51:03.980 --> 00:51:05.430
or you're not getting results.

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:06.480
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:51:06.480 --> 00:51:07.880
BERNARD ROTH: If you're
not getting the result

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:09.470
and you want to move
to the doing state,

00:51:09.470 --> 00:51:11.630
you have to say "There's
this chair in front of me,

00:51:11.630 --> 00:51:13.290
I have to walk around it."

00:51:13.290 --> 00:51:16.350
And the chair may
be a person or maybe

00:51:16.350 --> 00:51:18.970
the way you hold the world.

00:51:18.970 --> 00:51:22.040
But the point simply
is, that the reasons are

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:24.430
just irrelevant,
they're not necessary,

00:51:24.430 --> 00:51:27.036
they're not functional
at all, and mainly

00:51:27.036 --> 00:51:29.160
they're just a way of
letting yourself off the hook

00:51:29.160 --> 00:51:32.380
and blinding you as to
what the possibilities are.

00:51:32.380 --> 00:51:33.820
AUDIENCE: I see.

00:51:33.820 --> 00:51:35.320
I don't know if you
agree with this,

00:51:35.320 --> 00:51:36.903
but what you are
saying at some level,

00:51:36.903 --> 00:51:39.527
it's empowering that at
some level it's within us.

00:51:39.527 --> 00:51:41.610
And doesn't mean we need
to blame ourselves, or be

00:51:41.610 --> 00:51:43.677
hard on ourselves
overly, but you

00:51:43.677 --> 00:51:45.760
talk about this frame of
mind where at some point,

00:51:45.760 --> 00:51:46.600
"You know what, no.

00:51:46.600 --> 00:51:49.310
It isn't my boss's fault, or
it isn't the universe's fault,

00:51:49.310 --> 00:51:52.580
or this person's fault.
I just haven't gotten

00:51:52.580 --> 00:51:56.514
to the point where I've made the
connections and the decision."

00:51:56.514 --> 00:51:57.930
BERNARD ROTH: Well
what I call it,

00:51:57.930 --> 00:52:00.530
you have to have the
intention to do it and give it

00:52:00.530 --> 00:52:01.760
the attention.

00:52:01.760 --> 00:52:03.140
So it's as simple as that.

00:52:03.140 --> 00:52:05.290
A good example, I
was supposed to go

00:52:05.290 --> 00:52:07.120
to a meeting, which I
didn't want to go to,

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:09.650
in Texas, in Dallas.

00:52:09.650 --> 00:52:11.390
I got to the airport
in San Fransisco

00:52:11.390 --> 00:52:14.070
and the guards were good to
me, the airports in Texas

00:52:14.070 --> 00:52:16.020
were closed because
there was a snow storm.

00:52:16.020 --> 00:52:19.556
So I called up and I say,
"Really, I'm sorry I can't go."

00:52:19.556 --> 00:52:22.290
That's good, I went
home, I had a happy life.

00:52:22.290 --> 00:52:24.330
If I really wanted
to go to Texas,

00:52:24.330 --> 00:52:25.830
the fact that the
airport was closed

00:52:25.830 --> 00:52:26.780
wouldn't have stopped me.

00:52:26.780 --> 00:52:27.330
AUDIENCE: I see.

00:52:27.330 --> 00:52:29.020
BERNARD ROTH: It's as simple
as if my life depended

00:52:29.020 --> 00:52:31.440
upon getting to Texas, I
would've gotten to Texas even

00:52:31.440 --> 00:52:33.000
though the airport was closed.

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.230
But they gave me a gift,
they gave me an obstacle

00:52:35.230 --> 00:52:37.750
and I could just say
"I had a good reason."

00:52:37.750 --> 00:52:40.460
and they didn't say it.

00:52:40.460 --> 00:52:42.477
They didn't get this
whole idea that, "Yeah,

00:52:42.477 --> 00:52:44.060
so the airport's
closed, man, but when

00:52:44.060 --> 00:52:45.060
are you going to come here?"

00:52:45.060 --> 00:52:45.935
You know what I mean?

00:52:45.935 --> 00:52:49.360
If we were playing the
game at a high level,

00:52:49.360 --> 00:52:51.930
"Yeah, well you were committed
to going to the meeting,

00:52:51.930 --> 00:52:52.970
get here."

00:52:52.970 --> 00:52:55.820
But they didn't
do that, so, whew.

00:52:55.820 --> 00:52:57.697
MALE SPEAKER: Well, good stuff.

00:52:57.697 --> 00:53:00.280
Thanks for being here, we've got
a few books left in the back,

00:53:00.280 --> 00:53:02.234
the book is "The
Achievement Habit."

00:53:02.234 --> 00:53:03.900
Dr. Roth, thanks so
much for being here.

00:53:03.900 --> 00:53:05.450
[APPLAUSE]

